      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's dive into the physics of tensile stress and the bond between steel and concrete.\n\nWhen a tensile force is applied to a concrete structure, the concrete itself can't resist it very well, as you mentioned. This is because concrete has a relatively low tensile strength, typically around 1-3 MPa (depending on the type and quality of the concrete). However, the steel rebar can resist tensile forces much better, with a tensile strength of around 400-600 MPa.\n\nThe key to understanding the bond between steel and concrete lies in the concept of \"bonding\" or \"tensile bonding.\" When a tensile force is applied to the concrete, the steel rebar is able to transfer some of that force to the concrete, allowing it to resist the stress. This is achieved through the formation of a \"bonding layer\" between the steel and concrete, which is typically a thin layer of mortar or cement paste.\n\nThe bonding layer acts as a kind of \"grip\" between the steel and concrete, allowing them to work together to resist tensile forces. The steel rebar is able to resist the tensile forces, while the",
